│ THOUGHT: The miscompilation stems from InstCombine rewriting a guarded use of %in into an unconditional min/max use when the fast-math flags include ninf. With ninf, -inf as input      │
│ makes any FP op that consumes it poison. In the source, %add becomes poison for -inf but is not selected, so the function returns 1 safely. The transformation to maxnum(%in, 0)         │
│ unconditionally consumes %in, making the result poison and propagating it, which is more poisonous than the source. The fix is to prevent folding select into min/max when ninf is       │
│ present, since min/max would unconditionally evaluate with %in. I'll locate the select-to-min/max fold in InstCombine (likely in InstCombineSelectPatterns.cpp or related) and add a     │
│ guard to skip the transform if the FMF set hasNoInfs().                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ grep -Rn --line-number --color=auto -e "FoldSelect" -e "minmax" -e "llvm.maxnum" -e "select.*fcmp" llvm-project | sed -n '1,200p'                                                        │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
